The price-to-earnings ratio of a company refers to how much the company is worth to the investors. This is basically the company's stock price divided by its earnings per share for a particular time. 

Based on the table in the problem, the industry standard price-earnings ratio can be solved using this:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price-earnings ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{Stock price}}{\text{Earnings per share}}
\end{aligned}$$


Substituting the values, we will get:
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Industry standard price-earnings ratio}&=\dfrac{\$25.77}{\$0.96}\\[15 pt]
&=26.844
\end{aligned}$$
